result.execSummary:
The defendant James Everett Poole was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Drive or Operate Vehicle w/o Consent, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(3).
  • Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant James Everett Poole in court, in custody.  Attorney Theodore OReilly in court for James Everett Poole.  Attorney Alexander James Geocaris in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Case in court 
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant GUILTY AS TO COUNTS 1 and 3. 

AS TO COUNTS 2 and 4: Pursuant to negotiations and on the motion of the State, Court ordered charge DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing. Judgment of conviction entered.
Court advised defendant if they are not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, they could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  Court vacates the scheduled final pretrial and jury trial dates. 


Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties and defendant. 
AS TO COUNT 1: The Court sentenced the defendant to a maximum term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, concurrent with COUNT 3 and any other sentence, with credit for 61 DAYS time served; the term of initial confinement is is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS; the term of extended supervision is is 2 YEARS.  

AS TO COUNT 3: The Court sentenced the defendant to a maximum term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 3 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, concurrent with COUNT 1 and any other sentence, with credit for 61 DAYS time served; the term of initial confinement is is 1 YEAR AND 6 MONTHS; the term of extended supervision is is 2 YEARS.  

Court STAYED sentences in Counts 1 and 3 and placed defendant on probation for 2 YEARS.

Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.

Conditions of Probation/Extended Supervision
- As to Counts 1 and 3 concurrently: Serve 90 Days in the House of Correction as a condition time sentence, STAYED, to be used at discretion of Probation Agent. Huger release to be determined by HOC staff and Day Reporting Center.
- AODA assessment, comply with recommended treatment.
- Absolute sobriety, random urine screens at least 1 time per month.
- No use or possession of controlled substances without a valid prescription, no illegal drugs and no alcohol.
- No possession of drug paraphernalia.
- No contact or association with known drug dealers, drug houses and drug manufacturers. 
- Full time work, school or a combination. 
- No possession of firearms, ammunition, magazines, holsters, and body armor.
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.
- Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges (including DNA), during term of probation. If revoked, amount to be paid out of prison funds at a rate to be determined by DOC, balance paid during extended supervision. Failure to pay results in a civil judgment. 

Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for 6 months. 

Court will grant expungement upon successful completion of probation. 

Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting. 
Court advised defendant of his right to seek postconviction relief.
Appellate rights given.
